<br>
If someone makes an attempt at roleplaying, I like to join in.  I'm often surprised with how much fun it can be.  RP Police get on my nerves sometimes...I'm so tired of people complaing that if a dark elf groups with a human that it isn't RP.  I mean, wow.  It isn't like you know the story.  You just see two people around.<br>
<br>
I had an Ogre that didn't use the typical dumbspeak.  Some people like it, and that's fine, but to me it's been long gone a cliche.  So my Ogre with his 80 intelligence did not enjoy the company of other ogres.  Oddly enough, he had a begrudging respect for Barbarians and had a little love for gnomes.  I used to treat gnomes like you might treat your pet dog... something to pet, dote over, to not take seriously.  Barbarians to me were &quot;refined&quot; humans, living more like the way a human should live, more free of the corruption of the cities.  I came to these two ideas in that several gnomes had stopped to buff me or to duel me on my way from Oggok to Blackburrow, and that I was to respect barbarians when the ONLY person I could find to group with was a barbarian of good nature, and the person I sold all my hard earned loot to was in the barbarian camp by the waters edge as you're entering the karanas from qeynos hills.<br>
<br>
Yet I had all sorts of people insult my roleplaying.  Elves spamming messages in their confusing tongue saying that I shouldn't be grouped with a barbarian, and 1 rude ogre at Rathe Mtns who seemed upset that I hadn't come to his aid when he was fighting a gnome along the path to Lake Rathe.  Noone attempted to know my history.  It apalls me that I should go about screaming every little thing about my character just to justify my IC actions.<br>
<br>
*sigh*  I miss roleplaying evil.  It's so much easier than roleplaying neutrality...hehe. <p>Reoqim
